		<div class="entry-content"><div class="w592"><figure class="media photo promo" itemprop="associatedMedia" itemscope="" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/31/us/31RELIGIOUSFREEDOMJP2-LN/31RELIGIOUSFREEDOMJP2-tmagArticle-v2.jpg" itemtype="//schema.org/ImageObject" role="group"><span class="visually-hidden">Photo</span><div class="image"><img itemprop="url" itemid="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/31/us/31RELIGIOUSFREEDOMJP2-LN/31RELIGIOUSFREEDOMJP2-tmagArticle-v2.jpg" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/2015/03/31/us/31RELIGIOUSFREEDOMJP2-LN/31RELIGIOUSFREEDOMJP2-tmagArticle-v2.jpg" id="100000003603599" width="592" height="379" alt="Thousands gathered outside the Indiana Statehouse on Saturday to protest a law that opponents say allows for bias against gays. &lt;a href=&quot;//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/31/us/politics/religious-protection-laws-once-called-shields-are-now-seen-as-cudgels.html&quot;&gt;Related Article&lt;/a&gt;"   /><meta itemprop="height" content="379"><meta itemprop="width" content="592"></div><figcaption class="caption" itemprop="description"><span class="caption-text">Thousands gathered outside the Indiana Statehouse on Saturday to protest a law that opponents say allows for bias against gays. <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/31/us/politics/religious-protection-laws-once-called-shields-are-now-seen-as-cudgels.html">Related Article</a></span><span class="credit" itemprop="copyrightHolder"><span class="visually-hidden">Credit</span> Doug McSchooler/Associated Press</span></figcaption></figure></div>
<div id="sharetools-story" class="sharetools theme-classic sharetools-story" data-shares="email|Email,facebook|Share,twitter|Tweet,save|Save,show-all|More,ad" data-url="//learning.blogs.nytimes.com/2015/04/01/is-the-indiana-religious-freedom-law-an-invitation-to-discriminate-against-gays/" data-title="Is the Indiana Religious Freedom Law an &#8216;Invitation to Discriminate Against Gays&#8217;?" data-description="Have you been following the news about the storms of protest over a new Indiana law that could make it easier for religious conservatives to refuse service to gay couples? What is your reaction? Why?">
				<div class="ad sharetools-inline-article-ad"></div>
				<div id="MiddleLeft" class="ad middle-left-ad nocontent robots-nocontent"></div>
				</div><div class="w151 right module">
<div class="entry"><a title="See all Student Opinion" href="/category/student-opinion/"><img src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/learning/learning_student-opinion151.png" alt="Student Opinion - The Learning Network" /></a><a title="See all Student Opinion" href="/category/student-opinion/"><img class="w35 right" src="https://static01.nyt.com/images/blogs_v3/learning/learning_student-opinion35.png" alt="Student Opinion - The Learning Network" /></a></p>
<p class="summary">Questions about issues in the news for students 13 and older.</p>
<ul class="refer">
<li><a title="See all Student Opinion" href="/category/student-opinion/">See all Student Opinion Â»</a></li>
</ul>
</div>
</div>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Have you been following the news about the <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/28/us/politics/indiana-law-denounced-as-invitation-to-discriminate-against-gays.html">storms of protest</a> over a recently passed Indiana  law (and an <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/01/us/religious-freedom-restoration-act-arkansas-indiana.html">Arkansas bill</a>) that could make it easier for religious conservatives to refuse service to gay couples? </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">What is your reaction? Why?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><span id="more-156642"></span></p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">In <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/03/31/us/politics/religious-protection-laws-once-called-shields-are-now-seen-as-cudgels.html">&#8220;Religious Protection Laws, Once Called Shields, Are Now Seen as Cudgels,&#8221;</a> Erik Eckholm traces the history of the federal Religious Freedom Restoration Act and the current furor over the related law in Indiana:</p>
<blockquote><p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">When the federal government adopted a religious protection act in 1993, same-sex marriage was not on the horizon.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">An informal coalition of liberals and conservatives endorsed the Religious Freedom Restoration Act because it seemed to protect members of vulnerable religious minorities from punishment for the exercise of their beliefs. The federal legislation was set off by a case in which two followers of the Native American church were fired and denied unemployment benefits because they took part in ceremonies with peyote, an illegal drug.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">Twenty states, including Indiana last week, have since passed their own versions of religious freedom laws.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">But over time, court decisions and conservative legal initiatives started to change the meaning of those laws, according to liberal activists. The state laws were not used to protect minorities, these critics say, but to allow some religious groups to undermine the rights of women, gays and lesbians or other groups.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8230; In the 1990s, for example, in the kind of case that raised red flags for civil rights advocates, landlords cited religious beliefs, sometimes with success in court, after refusing to rent to unmarried heterosexual couples.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The clash of values erupted again after Indiana adopted its own version of a âreligious freedomâ act last week. Arkansas is expected to approve a similar law this week.</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">The furor has put Gov. Mike Pence of Indiana, who is considered a possible Republican presidential candidate, under national scrutiny. On Monday, Republican legislators in Indiana said they were searching with the governor for a possible amendment to the law to âclarifyâ that it does not permit discrimination against gays and lesbians.</p>
</blockquote>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Students:</strong> Read the entire article, then tell us &#8230;</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; Now that you have read the article, do you agree more with those who say that this law is discriminatory or with those who say that it protects religious liberty? Whichever you side with more, do you have some sympathy for points made by the other group? Why or why not?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; Gov. Mike Pence <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/01/us/governor-mike-pence-defends-indiana-religious-freedom-restoration-act.html">rejects</a> claims that the law would allow businesses to deny services to gays and lesbians and says that if it was about discrimination he would have vetoed it. What do you think? </p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; Why do legal experts say that this law is different from the original federal law? Why do civil rights experts say that religious freedom laws like this one include language that could open the way to even wider discrimination? How can you imagine that playing out?</p>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody">&#8212; The governor <a href="//www.nytimes.com/2015/04/01/us/governor-mike-pence-defends-indiana-religious-freedom-restoration-act.html">acknowledges</a> that the law has become a threat to the stateâs reputation and economy, with companies and organizations signaling that they will avoid Indiana in response to it. What do you think will happen to this law and laws like it? Why? </p>
<hr/>
<p class="story-body-text" itemprop="articleBody"><strong>Students 13 and older</strong> are invited to comment below. Please use only your <strong>first name.</strong> For <a href="//www.nytimes.com/ref/membercenter/help/privacysummary.html">privacy policy</a> reasons, we will not publish student comments that include a last name.</p>
	</div>
